# TC Scaffolder Environment Variables Example
#
# Copy this file to .env in your project root and fill in your values.
# IMPORTANT: Add .env to your .gitignore to prevent committing secrets!
#
# Usage:
#   cp lib/scaffolder/examples/.env.example .env
#   # Edit .env with your values
#   echo ".env" >> .gitignore
#   tc scaffold my-app

# ============================================================================
# LLM Provider Configuration
# ============================================================================

# Provider selection: "bedrock" or "anthropic"
# Default: bedrock
TC_LLM_PROVIDER=bedrock

# Model identifier
# For Bedrock: anthropic.claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022-v2:0
# For Anthropic: claude-sonnet-4-5-20250929
# Default: Provider-specific default
TC_LLM_MODEL=anthropic.claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022-v2:0

# ============================================================================
# AWS Bedrock Configuration (only needed if using Bedrock)
# ============================================================================

# AWS Region where Bedrock is available
# Common regions: us-east-1, us-west-2, eu-west-1
# Default: AWS SDK default region resolution
AWS_REGION=us-east-1

# AWS Profile name (from ~/.aws/config or ~/.aws/credentials)
# Default: "default" or AWS SDK default profile
AWS_PROFILE=my-profile

# AWS Access Key (alternative to profile-based auth)
# Not recommended: Use profiles or SSO instead for better security
# AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=your-access-key-id
# AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=your-secret-access-key
# AWS_SESSION_TOKEN=your-session-token  # Optional, for temporary credentials

# ============================================================================
# Anthropic API Configuration (only needed if using Anthropic provider)
# ============================================================================

# Anthropic API Key
# Get your key from: https://console.anthropic.com
# Required when TC_LLM_PROVIDER=anthropic
CLAUDE_API_KEY=sk-ant-your-api-key-here

# ============================================================================
# Configuration Precedence
# ============================================================================
#
# TC resolves configuration in this order (highest to lowest priority):
# 1. CLI Parameters (--llm-provider, --llm-model, --aws-region, --aws-profile)
# 2. Environment Variables (this file or shell environment)
# 3. Config File (config.toml)
# 4. Defaults (bedrock provider, provider-specific model)
#
# Shell environment variables take precedence over .env file values.

# ============================================================================
# Examples
# ============================================================================

# Example 1: AWS Bedrock with SSO
# TC_LLM_PROVIDER=bedrock
# AWS_PROFILE=my-sso-profile
# AWS_REGION=us-east-1
# (Run: aws sso login --profile my-sso-profile)

# Example 2: AWS Bedrock with default credentials
# TC_LLM_PROVIDER=bedrock
# AWS_REGION=us-east-1
# (Credentials from ~/.aws/credentials or environment)

# Example 3: Anthropic API
# TC_LLM_PROVIDER=anthropic
# CLAUDE_API_KEY=sk-ant-your-api-key-here
# TC_LLM_MODEL=claude-sonnet-4-5-20250929

# Example 4: Development with fast/cheap model
# TC_LLM_PROVIDER=bedrock
# TC_LLM_MODEL=anthropic.claude-3-haiku-20240307-v1:0
# AWS_PROFILE=development

# Example 5: Production with most capable model
# TC_LLM_PROVIDER=bedrock
# TC_LLM_MODEL=anthropic.claude-3-opus-20240229-v1:0
# AWS_PROFILE=production
# AWS_REGION=us-west-2

# ============================================================================
# Security Notes
# ============================================================================
#
# 1. NEVER commit this file with real credentials to version control
# 2. Add .env to your .gitignore file
# 3. Use different .env files for different environments
# 4. Rotate API keys and access keys regularly
# 5. Use AWS SSO or IAM roles when possible (more secure than access keys)
# 6. Grant only necessary permissions (bedrock:InvokeModel for Bedrock)
#
# To verify your .env is not tracked by git:
#   git status  # Should not show .env
#   cat .gitignore | grep .env  # Should show .env

# ============================================================================
# Troubleshooting
# ============================================================================
#
# If TC is not using your .env values:
# 1. Verify .env is in the current directory (where you run tc)
# 2. Check for shell environment variables that override .env
# 3. Verify .env file syntax (KEY=value, no spaces around =)
# 4. Check for typos in variable names
# 5. Ensure no quotes around values (unless the value contains spaces)
#
# To debug:
#   cat .env  # View your .env file
#   env | grep TC_LLM  # Check environment variables
#   env | grep AWS  # Check AWS variables
#   env | grep CLAUDE  # Check Anthropic variables
